{
  "text": "Soil water is a component of soil, a vital water resource, and a frequent subject of soil physics investigations. An improved understanding of water movement and distribution in soil profile would benefit field irrigation determination and water use efficiency [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . However, droughts often occur in many parts of the world, and they usually have devastating effects on crop growth and production [3] . In arid and semiarid regions, low levels of rainfall, high rates of atmospheric evaporation, and weak water retention often result in cultivated soils having poor production [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Reducing water loss and extending the duration for which water is maintained in soil could help crops to absorb moisture, thereby improving water use efficiency. Infiltration and evaporation are key factors resulting in water loss from soil [CITATION_5] ; as inalienable parts of the water cycle, both processes determine the soil water balance and the degree of effective utilization of irrigation water. They are also key factors restricting agricultural planting [CITATION_6] . Therefore, investigations of water distribution due to infiltration and evaporation are required to develop effective approaches to enhance soil water-holding capacity and promote the healthy development of farming [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] .",
